<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-755-473  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 755 473.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 19 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Xerox to continue to pay those on active duty.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Xerox Corp. (Personnel management).andO;Ticker:    XRX.andO;Topic:     Computer industryMilitaryWagesPersonnel ManagementIraq-Kuwait Crisis, 1990-.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>XEROX TO CONTINUE TO PAY THOSE ON ACTIVE DUTY 12/19/90 STAMFORD, CONNECTICUT,U.S.A., 1990 DEC 19 (NB) -- Xerox Corporation has announced that it willcontinue to pay its employees who have been called to active military duty anincome supplement equal to the difference between their military pay and whatthey receive as compensation from the company.andM;Xerox states that this action extends a temporary pay policy enhancementbegun in August from 180 days to a maximum of 360 days to correspond with thenew minimum period of service set by the government.andP;  Involved Xeroxemployees called to active duty by military reserve or National Guard unitsand their dependents also will continue to be provided medical and dentalcoverage for up to 360 days.andP;  The temporary adjustment of the Xerox militaryleave of absence policy becomes effective with the commencement of anindividual employee's active duty.andM;An estimated 200 of the company's more than 66,000 employees in the UnitedStates are members of the reserves or National Guard.andP;  As of Dec. 13, 38Xerox people had been called up.andP;  The Xerox statement said that the companyis taking the action &quot;to minimize some of the financial hardships andinsecurity for those employees and their dependents caused by their call upto active duty.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19901219/Press Contact: Dean J.andO;Golembeski, Xerox, 203-968-3572 )</TEXT></DOC>